sec.p:
Human papillomavirus (HPV) is one of the most prevalent sexually transmitted infections. It is so common that nearly all sexually active people have it at some point in their lives, according to the information provided by the United States’ Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC)16. Generally, the infection disappears on its own without inducing any health problem, but in some cases it can produce an abnormal growth of cells on the surface of the cervix that could potentially lead to cervical cancer. HPV infection is also related to other cancers (vulva, vagina, penis, anus, \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\ldots$$\end{document}…) and other diseases like genital warts (GW). The fact that most cases of HPV infection are asymptomatic causes that public health registries might be potentially underestimating its incidence. The underreporting phenomenon in HPV data from the discrete time series point of view has been recently studied7.

Consider an unobservable process with an AutoRegressive Moving Average (ARMA(p, r)) structure defined by1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
